3. Map a continuous variable to color, size, and shape. How do these aesthetics behave differently for categorical vs.continuous variables?

Mapping continuous and categorical variables to color:

Continuous:
ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=cyl, y=hwy, color=displ))

Categorical:
ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=cyl, y=hwy, color=drv))

The color aesthetic behaves differently when mapped to continuous versus categorical variables in that there is a different relationship between the colors it selects to represent each type of variable. For continuous variables, it provides a color gradient to illustrate where values are extreme. For categorical variables, it chooses colors with maximum contrast so that categories can be differentiated.

Mapping continuous and categorical variables to size:

Continuous:
ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=cyl, y=hwy, size=displ))

Categorical:
ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=cyl, y=hwy, size=drv))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

The size aesthetic behaves differently when mapped to continuous versus categorical variables in that for continuous variables, there is a relationship between the size of the point and the value of the variable: the size of the point increases as the value of the variable increases. For categorical variables, the size of the point has no relationship to the variables categories, since the categories have no order to them.

Mapping continuous and categorical variables to shape:

Continuous:
#ggplot(data=mpg) +
#  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=cyl, y=hwy, shape=displ))

Running this code produces the following error message: Error: A continuous variable can not be mapped to shape

Categorical:
ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=cyl, y=hwy, shape=drv))

The shape aesthetic behaves differently when mapped to continuous versus categorical variables in that it doesnt work for continuous variables (presumably because it doesnt make sense to represent each value of the variable with a different shape). For categorical variables, shape represents each category with a different shape.

4. What happens if you map the same variable to multiple aesthetics?

If you map the same variable to multiple aesthetics, the graph combines the aesthetics. In the below scatterplot, drv is mapped to both color and shape, and so each category of drv is represented by a unique shape-color combination.

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=cyl, y=hwy, color=drv, shape=drv))

5. What does the stroke aesthetic do? What shapes does it work with? (Hint: use ?geom_point)

?geom_point

The stroke aesthetic works with the filled shapes, 21 through 24, for which you can control the appearance of both the fill color and the outline. For those shapes, stroke changes the width of the outline.

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=cyl, y=hwy), shape=21, color="green", stroke=2)

6. What happens if you map an aesthetic to something other than a variable name, like aes(colour = displ < 5)?

If you map an aesthetic to a statement, rather than to a variable name, it applies a different visual effect to each observation according to whether the statement is true for the observation or not. In the below graph, observations for which displ<5 is true are colored blue, whereas observations for which displ<5 is false are colored orange.

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=cyl, y=hwy, color = displ<5))

Section 3.5.1

4. Take the first faceted plot in this section:

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

What are the advantages to using faceting instead of the colour aesthetic? What are the disadvantages? How might the balance change if you had a larger dataset?

The advantage to using faceting rather than the color aesthetic is that faceting enables you to clearly see how observations are distributed for each category of a certain variable. If you were using the color aesthetic without facets, it would be more difficult to see the distribution of observations by category because they would all be in one large plot, and points from different categories may overlap with each other. However, using the color aesthetic rather than facets could highlight how one category relates to the other categories or differs from them in the context of all of the observations. This would be harder to see in a faceted plot because each category is displayed separately from the others. In a larger dataset, faceting might be more advantageous, since with more observations it might be harder to see in one plot how variables of different categories might differ from each other.

5. Read ?facet_wrap. What does nrow do? What does ncol do? What other options control the layout of the individual panels? Why doesnt facet_grid() have nrow and ncol argument?

?facet_wrap

nrow specifies the number of rows of panels in the faceted plot, while ncol specifies the number of columns of panels in the plot. Another option that controls the layout of the individual panels is scales, which allows the scales to be the same across each panel or to vary across panels.
facet_grid() doesnt have nrow or ncol arguments because the number of rows and columns is defined by the levels of the two variables that are specified to make the grid.

2. Run this code in your head and predict what the output will look like. Then, run the code in R and check your predictions.

I predict that the code will create a scatterplot of hwy by displ where the points are colored according to the categories of drv. The plot will also include smooth lines for each of the categories of drv, and those lines will also be colored accordingly.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

3. What does show.legend = FALSE do? What happens if you remove it? Why do you think I used it earlier in the chapter?

show.legend = FALSE removes the graphs legend, which tells what each of the group aesthetics represents. When you remove show.legend=FALSE, the legend appears by default if the graph uses aesthetics by group. It was used earlier in the chapter in an example including 3 graphs, not all of which were grouped by an aesthetic, and this was done in order to make all graphs in the example consistent.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point(show.legend = FALSE) + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, show.legend = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

4. What does the se argument to geom_smooth() do?

The se argument to geom_smooth() specifies whether or not to include a representation of the confidence interval around the line in the graph.

5. Will these two graphs look different? Why/why not?

The two graphs will not look different, because specifying mappings in the overall ggplot() function will define them as global mappings that will be passed to each of the geoms that are added to the graph.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_smooth(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

Section 3.7.1

2. What does geom_col() do? How is it different to geom_bar()?

geom_col() and geom_bar() both create bar charts. However, with geom_col(), the height of the bars represents the values of the variable defined in aesthetic y. Meanwhile, with geom_bar() the height of the bars represents the number of cases in each group.

Answer this question:

1. Look at the data graphics at the following link: What is a Data Scientist. Please briefly critique the designers choices. What works? What doesnt work? What would you have done differently?

I think the most effective graphics the designer used were the bar charts (used to compare data scientists to business intelligence professionals), because its clear from the differences in the height of the bars that data scientists do differ from business intelligence professionals in the ways that the text points out. The choice of blue and dark gray as the two colors to represent each group is maybe not as effective, since there isnt much contrast between those colors. There are certain graphics that use size to illustrate differences (the squares representing responses to the question about the best source of new data science talent, and circles representing the fields that data scientists and BI professionals studied). These graphics are somewhat effective in the sense that the viewer can clearly tell which category is the biggest and what the relative size of the other categories is, but their effectiveness was undercut because I was confused about how the percentage mapped to the area of the circles/squares: for example, the 12% square is about a fourth the size of the 24% square (I later realized that the percentages likely map to the height of the squares/circles, not their area.) Still, if viewers are paying attention to area, this representation would exaggerate the differences between the categories. Its especially confusing for the circles, since its harder to compare the heights of the circles.

In general, I would have organized this series of graphics in a more logical manner, so that the graphic as a whole tells a more coherent story. For one thing, there are several graphics that compare data scientists to business intelligence professionals, but theyre scattered throughout, rather than grouped together to provide a clear picture of how data scientists tend to differ from business intelligence professionals. I might have started with the graphics that provide background for who data scientists are and what they do, then included a section comparing data scientists to business intelligence professionals, and then ended with the graphics about the future of the data science workforce.
